<div class="post"><div class="posttop"><div class="username">Zumino Zufeilon</div><div class="date">May 18th, 2011, 09:09 PM</div></div><div class="posttext">As someone who has been tested in the top 0.1% of ADD cases**, avoid any &quot;smart&quot; pills, or focus pills.  That isn't what they are really doing.  They are depressing/altering the natural thought processes that you have built and are used to, and usually in very harmful ways, long term.<br />
<br />
I'm a ABD (All But Dissertation) Doctoral Candidate, which, as my advisor said, means I have developed a VERY healthy adaptation to ADD.  I'm a &quot;success story&quot; for ADD/ADHD, and I've talked with dozens of families/kids over the years, the important thing is to learn, and adapt your habits to encourage constructive application of the ADD/ADHD, not treat it into oblivion with drugs.  Firstly, they drugs loose their effectiveness with time, and secondly, they loose their effectiveness with age.  Learning, at an early age, the adaptive behaviors that work for you is the best option, bar none.  But the most important reason to adapt instead of drug is simple.  ADD/ADHD is actually a tremendous advantage in and of itself, you just have to sharpen the upsides, while minimizing the downsides.<br />
<br />
This requires a VERY high level of metacognition.  Paying attention to what helps you actually understand, not &quot;learn well enough for a test&quot;, but truly understand.  It is different for each person, but some helpful tricks that 'usually' work are:<br />
1) High doses (relatively) of Caffine.  Caffine mimicks the mind-altering effects of Adderall/Ritalin, but does so at a much lower level, and is controllable by how much you drink of it.<br />
<br />
2) A low-level external stimulation (I use music or movies that I've heard/seen over 20 times personally), that way I've got it memorized, I don't need to pay attention at all, but it acts as a distractor for the part of my brain that tries, and needs to be distracted.<br />
<br />
3) Frequent, short, study sessions instead of long slog study sessions.  The long hauls DO NOT WORK.  Study for 30-45 minutes, and take a 15 minute break.  This is a very, very key one.  And it's the hardest for people to adapt to, because it requires starting early on projects/papers/homeworks.  Putting things off to the last minute absolutely, positively destroys your ability to understand the material, and makes it even harder to succeed.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
**I was 'diagnosed' formally as a part of university, they wanted me to take a test to prove I was ADD, which amused me, as if a test could really document that. . .  The doctor who is in charge of 'grading' the test commented that he had never, ever, seen a 'higher score' then on my test.  Too which I replied &quot;no shit, Sherlock&quot;.</div></div><hr />


