Wow, your description there of ways you deal with ADD/ADHD perfectly match the habits I have formed over the years for exactly the same reason. I have never been &quot;diagnosed&quot; by a doctor with any mental disorders, but I've suspected for many years now that this was the case.<br />
<br />
I have also discovered that meditation is incredibly difficult, and even more beneficial. I only dose caffeen in the morning hours because if I drink any after 3PM or so I won't be able to sleep without difficulty. I almost always have music or movies running in the background, I casually joke about some movies that have made it to my &quot;hundred club&quot; - movies that I've &quot;watched&quot; over 100+ times. I spend entire days switching among different tasks every hour, trying to keep focused on one thing for more than 45 minutes is nearly impossible for me (with the exception of reading books, I can usually handle that for 2-3 hour sessions, or more if the book is really good). When I went back to school, I found that my math homework typically took me two hours a night, but I'd have to get up and take a walk for 10-15 minutes once an hour to keep at it.<br />
<br />
As it turns out, I just listened to what my body and mind were telling me and did what needed to be done. I'm not convinced there's anything more to it. I sleep when I'm tired, I change tasks when I'm bored, I take a break when I can't focus.</div></div><hr />


